@node CONTENTS "CNet Amiga Pager's Table of Contents"
     CNet Amiga Pager, @{"v5.20" link "!PagerHISTORY.guide/MAIN"} README File by @{"Dotoran of Frontiers BBS!" link !PagerHISTORY.guide/FRONTIERS}
===========================================================================
                   @{" General Description of CNet Amiga Pager " link GENERAL}

                   @{" What to do with earlier Pager versions! " link UPGRADE}

                       @{" How to install CNet Amiga Pager " link INSTALL}

       @{" Using Pager's CONFIG file " link CONFIG}    @{" Using Pager's SysAvail Editor " link SYSAVAIL}

       @{" What the program does     " link DOES}    @{" Using Pager's SYS command     " link SYSCOMMAND}

                         @{" What ScripIt and/or Xit do " link SCRIPIT}

             @{" Final words, acknowledgments, ideas for the future? " link THANKS}
@endnode
@node GENERAL "What Is It?"
@toc CONTENTS
    A NEW Chat command written specifically for CNet Amiga BBS! It will
perform the same function as CNet's built-in chat function, however also
gives the SysOp MANY, MANY more functions they can perform!

    Version 5.20 allows for Multiple SysOps, so after the Pager has been set
up, the user will be asked WHICH SysOp they wish to Page.

    After the reason has been entered, a requestor will pop up on the FRONT
MOST screen shortly after the specified SOUND file has been played, and
the specified SPEECH has been orated. This requestor tells you which port
requested the chat, the date and time the chat request was made, any SysOp
Comment on file, the handle and real name of the user, and the reason why
they wish to chat.

    There is also the option to have CNet use the CC command to send a
"Chat Request OLM" if a SysOp happens to be somewhere online, instead of
being disturbed by an annoying requestor. This will ONLY be done if the
requesting user has ACCESS to use the CC command. If they do NOT have
access to use CC, then a regular page will be attempted.

    If you are NOT available, Pager will display your custom "SysOp OUT"
reason for that HOUR of that DAY. All 24 hours of all 7 days can receive a
unique "SysOp OUT" reason. (Using MCI Commands, you could even have the
reason display a TEXT file if you feel a more lengthy reason is needed at
times.)

      On the requestor CNet Amiga Pager displays are eight buttons:

    @{"CHAT" link CHAT}  @{"OLM" link OLM}  @{"FSEND" link FSEND}  @{"TERMINATE" link TERMINATE}  @{"GONE IN 5" link GONEIN5}  @{"UNAVAILABLE" link UNAVAILABLE}  @{"BUSY" link BUSY}  @{"IGNORE" link IGNORE}

    Whenever any of the above buttons has been pressed, the requestor will
be removed from the screen, and the appropriate action(s) will be performed,
as well as the "Reason" for chatting being removed from CNet memory, which
means it should stop flashing in the Control Panel window.

    The user is "told" of the action you've taken in the form of a colorized
System OLM that will be sent. When the "Ignore" option is used, NO OLM's are
sent to the user. When the "OLM" button is used, the default bbstext colors
will be used when sending the olm message.
@endnode
@node CHAT "The CHAT button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"Chat" - [ Uses "C" as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~~
    - Will alert the user you are coming to chat with them by sending them
      a "System OLM Message". (These messages interrupt into whatever the
      user is currently doing, provided their current activity isn't set to
      block these OLM's). System OLM Messages can NOT be responded to.
@endnode
@node OLM "The OLM button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"OLM" - [ Uses "O" as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~
    - Allows you to send a customized System OLM to the user, instead of
      actually having to chat with them. After selecting this button, you'll
      be given another requestor with three buttons: (Use the RAMIGA key in
      conjunction with the alternative key to activate these buttons).

          "Send" - [ Use RAMIGA - S as an alternative to the mouse! ]
           ~~~~
              - The text entered in the string gadget will be sent to the
                user as a System OLM Message. Normally, you'd simply press
                RETURN to send the text, but you CAN press SEND instead.

              - Pressing RETURN with NO text in the string gadget will
                activate the IGNORE button, which functions the EXACT same
                way as the main IGNORE button, described below.

          "Cancel" - [ Use RAMIGA - C as an alternative to the mouse! ]
           ~~~~~~
              - This will abort the sending of the OLM Message, and return
                you to the main Pager Requestor, allowing you to make a
                different choice on what you'd like to do for/to the user.

          "Ignore" - [ Uses RAMIGA - I as an alternative to the mouse! ]
           ~~~~~~
              - Acts the same as the IGNORE button described below.

              - This button will also be activated if you press RETURN
                with NO text in the string gadget!

    - While you're sitting in the String Gadget, you can activate any of
      the buttons by pressing RAMIGA-Hot Key, as defined above.
@endnode
@node FSEND "The FSEND button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"FSend" - [Uses "F" as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~~~
    - Will give you a file requestor you can use to ADD files to the user's
      Select Buffer.
    - Use the MOUSE to select multiple files by holding down the SHIFT key,
      then selecting those files you wish to add.
    - Use the Up and Down arrows with RETURN if you'll only be adding ONE
      file, as an alternative to using the mouse.
    - Click the "Done" button(or press RAMIGA-D) to complete the procedure.
    - As many of the files will be added to the user's Select Buffer as are
      possible. This means if you have it set in your CNET CONFIG that users
      can only select 10 files at a time, and you specify you wish to add 20
      files to the user's Select Buffer, only the first 10 files would be
      added(provided the user's Select Buffer was EMPTY to start with). If
      this should ever occur, the OLM that is sent to the user will let them
      know what has occurred.
    - The user will be charged for the download, based on your setting in
      the Pager CONFIG file. Certain config settings may also provide you
      with additional requestors allowing you to select specific costs for
      each individual file.
    - The file will be killed after the download, also based on your
      setting in the Pager CONFIG file. Again, additional requestors MAY be
      provided for you to select specific kill settings for each file IF
      you have it set that way in the config file.
@endnode
@node TERMINATE "The TERMINATE button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"Terminate" - [ Uses "T" as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~~~~~~~
    - Will immediately drop that user's time remaining to 0, then drop
      carrier. (For those users who continually hound you to Chat!)

    - This will happen for ANY user, INCLUDING those with INFINITE time,
      and INCLUDING those with "System Operator" status!

    - A System OLM message will be sent to the user, with a slight pause
      after sending it, so that the user will be sure to SEE it before the
      program terminates their connection.
@endnode
@node GONEIN5 "The GONE IN 5 button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"Gone In 5" - [ Uses "G" as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~~~~~~~
    - Similar to the above, but will allow the user 5 minutes to finish up
      anything they may have been doing(Posting, Responding, etc.)

    - This will happen for ANY user, INCLUDING those with INFINITE time,
      and INCLUDING those with "System Operator" status!
@endnode
@node UNAVAILABLE "The UNAVAILABLE button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"Unavailable" - [ Uses "U" as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~~~~~~~~~
    - Will inform the user you are no longer available to chat, and will
      additionally disable the "Sysop is in" checkmark for that port. More
      information on this below.
@endnode
@node BUSY "The BUSY button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"Busy" - [ Uses "B" as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~~
    - Similar to the above, but will simply tell the user you are too BUSY
      to chat, while still maintaining your "Sysop is in" status.
@endnode
@node IGNORE "The IGNORE button..."
@toc CONTENTS
"Ignore" - [ Uses RETURN as an alternative to the mouse! ]
 ~~~~~~
    - Will deactivate the requestor, WITHOUT alerting the user you are
      doing so. (If you simply do NOT want to be bothered).
@endnode
@node INSTALL "How Do I Install It?"
@toc CONTENTS
   There are 12 steps involved in CNet Amiga Pager's installation:

            1. @{"Choosing between ScripIt or Xit.           " link INSTALL1}
            2. @{"Copying needed external libraries.         " link INSTALL2}
            3. @{"Copying the `Pager/' directory.            " link INSTALL3}
            4. @{"Adding the CHAT command to BBSMENU.        " link INSTALL4}
            5. @{"Adding the SYS command to BBSMENU.         " link INSTALL5}
            6. @{"Edit line 920 (System OLM) in BBSTEXT.     " link INSTALL6}
            7. @{"Edit line 99 (Logoff Complete) in BBSTEXT. " link INSTALL7}
            8. @{"Saving & Reloading BBSMENU & BBSTEXT files." link INSTALL8}
            9. @{"Creating the CNet CRON Event to run AMaint." link INSTALL9}
           10. @{"Launching the Pager CONFIG editor.         " link INSTALL10}
           11. @{"Launching the Pager SYSAVAIL editor.       " link INSTALL11}
           12. @{"Installing Sound & Speech Programs.        " link INSTALL12}
@endnode
@node INSTALL1 "Installation Step 1..."
@toc CONTENTS
 1: An intuition-script language is used to close requestors created by
    Pager. This program is called ScripIt. There are two versions included
    in this package: ScripIt and Xit. You can opt to use EITHER one, but
    I'd suggest starting with the Xit program, as this will give you a 20K
    savings. Choose one of these files and copy it to your C: directory.

    NOTE: ScripIt is a scipting language that allows you to create scripts
          to mimic intuitionized events, like opening windows, pressing
          buttons, selecting items from menus, etc. You can find v1.20 on
          both Fred Fish Disk # 288, and on Disk A, Set I of the 4 CD-Rom
          AmiNet Set, if you'd like to take a look at it. Although written
          for WB 1.3, provided you don't get too fancy with your scripts,
          it will also work under WB 2.x and WB 3.x as well!
@endnode
@node INSTALL2 "Installation Step 2..."
@toc CONTENTS
 2: Copy both the "reqtools.library" and the "rexxreqtools.library" into
    your LIBS: directory.

   NOTE1: The complete "rexxreqtools.library" package can be found in the
          AmiNet Collection for anyone interested in obtaining it for your
          own use.
@endnode
@node INSTALL3 "Installation Step 3..."
@toc CONTENTS
 3: Copy the "Pager/" directory anywhere you wish. DOORS: is a recommended
    storage location, but the choice is yours.
@endnode
@node INSTALL4 "Installation Step 4..."
@toc CONTENTS
 4: In your BBSMENU file, in Menu # 2, the Available Everywhere Menu, locate
    the "Chat" command and place a "2" in front of the word, so it will look
    like this: 2Chat. Then, to the end of Menu # 2, add this line:

        Chat    `1- | {#0doors:Pager/PagerChat}
                |     |  ~\\|/~~~~~~~~
                |     |    |
                |     |    `--> This path should MATCH the path you stored
                |     |         the "Pager/" directory in Step # 3 above...
                |     |
                |     `-----> A Control-Q character.
                |
                `---------> This states Access Groups 1 thru 31 can use the
                            Chat command. (Change this to suit your needs)

    NOTE: The built-in CNet CHAT command will still work, but the user will
          need to type "2C", instead of "C" to use it. Also, although the
          Pager is written to play the same Chat Sound as CNet uses, your
          BBSTEXT Line 61 is NOT what loads and plays the sound. use the
          Pager CONFIG to modify the Sound that IS played.
@endnode
@node INSTALL5 "Installation Step 5..."
@toc CONTENTS
 5: Also add the following command to your Menu # 2 (Available Everywhere).
    This command is used to enter the CONFIG, edit the SysOp-Out Reasons, as
    well as allowing you to change your Availability Status for ANY Port.

        SYSop   `31 | {#0doors:Pager/PagerMaint}
                |     |  ~\\|/~~~~~~~~
                |     |    |
                |     |    `--> This path should MATCH the path you stored
                |     |         the "Pager/" directory in # 3 above...
                |     |
                |     `-----> A Control-Q character.
                |
                `---------> This specifies it's a "SysOp Only" command.

    NOTE: We've added this command to Menu # 2, instead of Menu # 1, so
          that you can choose to give access to this command to other users,
          maybe Co-SysOps or something, simply by editing the `31 above...
@endnode
@node INSTALL6 "Installation Step 6..."
@toc CONTENTS
 6: Load your BBSTEXT file and go to line number 920:

        \\n1\\c7**** System Message\\n1\\a1\\@1

    In order for the colored OLM Messages to work correctly, you need to
    REMOVE the \\@1 at the END of this line, so that the MCI Commands may be
    interpreted correctly. If you DON'T remove this command, all OLM's sent
    will look like the line above(with all MCI commands shown). I haven't
    seen/had any adverse effects by doing this, so it shouldn't pose any
    problems with other System Messages sent by CNet.

    You may also wish to take a second to "spruce up" the look of this line,
    perhaps by giving it some new colors, or changing the wording, etc. The
    user's will see this line displayed on their screens whenever you click
    one of the buttons on the Pager's requestor(except the IGNORE button).
@endnode
@node INSTALL7 "Installation Step 7..."
@toc CONTENTS
 7: While BBSTEXT is still loaded, go to line number 99:

        @ Logoff complete\\n1

    To the END of this line, add the following MCI command:

        {#0doors:Pager/PagerCleanUp}
        ^  ~~~~~^~~~~~~
        |       `--> This path should MATCH the one used in Step # 3 above.
        |
        `--> A Control-Q character.

    NOTE: There may be other MCI load commands added to this line for other
          programs, so you'll want to make sure the above command comes
          BEFORE any other MCI commands.

    NOTE: This is the script used to launch the Xit program that closes the
          requestor if the user should log off before you answer the page.
          If you opt to use the "Scripit" program, INSTEAD of the "Xit"
          program, you'll need to modify this program. You should change
          the filename from "Xit" to "ScripIt", as well as changing the
          extension of the ScripIt script from ".scx" to ".sc".
@endnode
@node INSTALL8 "Installation Step 8..."
@toc CONTENTS
 8: Save your BBSTEXT and BBSMENU files, then use the RAMIGA-T key combo to
    reload your BBSTEXT and BBSMENU files into CNet Memory, then...
@endnode
@node INSTALL9 "Installation Step 9..."
@toc CONTENTS
 9: Load your CNet CRON program and create the following NEW event:

                Name: PagerAMnt
          Event Type: RunARexx
             Port(s): 0
        Execute Date: <current date> with an hour ENDING in :00.
              Invoke: Immediate-NoDump
         Repeat Days: 0
        Repeat Hours: 1
         Repeat Mins: 0
          Valid Time: 00:59     /* In case another event is also running. */
              Status: Ready
       Unloaded Port: Ignore
          Check Days: Check ALL SEVEN
             Command: doors:Pager/PagerAMaint
                      ~~~~~^~~~~~~
                           `--> Use same path specified in Step # 3 above.

    NOTE: The AMaint file will run EVERY HOUR of EVERY DAY. It's quite small
          and will actually do NOTHING unless it HAS to. The file is used to
          toggle the global "Sysop is in" checkmark in your Control Panel's
          "ALL ports" menu. 
@endnode
@node INSTALL10 "Installation Step 10..."
@toc CONTENTS
10: Logon to your bbs, then type the following at a command prompt:

                                SYS CONFIG

    The "CNet Pager Config" file should then be loaded. Edit the fields to
    hold the info you will be using, then press ESC to SAVE the info. The
    CONFIG file will be explained FULLY below.
@endnode
@node INSTALL11 "Installation Step 11..."
@toc CONTENTS
11: Next, type this command at a command prompt:

                                SYS AVAIL

    The "CNet Pager Sysop-Out/Availability Editor" will be loaded. Use this
    file to create your "Sysop-Out" reasons, as well as your global "Sysop
    is in" hours. (The ones used by the AMAINT file above). More specific
    information is located below the detail given for the CONFIG file.
@endnode
@node INSTALL12 "Installation Step 12..."
@toc CONTENTS
12: Also included in the archive are programs you can use to play sounds and
    produce speech which can be used by CNet Amiga Pager. Do the following
    with the included files:

        SOUND
        ~~~~~
            I've only included the file "Sound" to be used for playing any
            sound data files you may wish to use. If you'd like to use this
            program to play sound on YOUR system, copy it to your C: dir.

            If you have another program you'd like to use instead of SOUND,
            make sure it's located somewhere in your PATH assignment, and
            that you type the appropriate launch line in the CONFIG program.
            Use the TEST SOUND command to make sure you have the arguments
            and paths set correctly.

        SPEECH
        ~~~~~~
            I've included two ways to create speech on your computer. You
            can opt to use either one:

            If you'd like to use "SAY", then copy it to your C: directory,
            then load the CONFIG program and go down to "Speech Options"
            and press your ENTER key. Delete whatever may currently be in
            that field, then type the word "say" and press ENTER. You'll be
            presented with the built-in default format for use with the
            "Say" program. Try the TEST SPEECH command to see how it sounds.
            Play with the values given after the -f, -s, and -p arguments to
            change how the speech will be orated.

            If you'd like to use the SPEAK: handler instead, you should do
            the following:

                - Copy the "narrator.device" to your DEVS: directory.
                - Copy the "translator.library" to your LIBS: directory.
                - Copy the "speak-handler" to your L: directory.
                - If using WB 2.04, then add the SPEAK: entry to the file
                  "mountlist", located in your DEVS: directory.
                - If using WB 2.1 or later, copy the "SPEAK" file into the
                  DEVS:DOSDrivers/ directory.
                - You should now REBOOT your system (cold, not warm).

            After rebooting, logon to the bbs and enter the Pager Config by
            typing "SYS CONFIG" from any command prompt and go down to the
            "Speech Options" item. Type "speak" and press ENTER to use the
            built-in defaults for use with the SPEAK: handler. From what I
            have been able to discern, there is no way to modify the way the
            speech sounds using this version of the SPEAK: handler, which is
            why I prefer using the older "SAY" program, however use the TEST
            SPEECH command and see how the speech sounds when using SPEAK:
            and decide for yourself which you'd like to use.
@endnode
@node CONFIG "How to Use Pager's Config"
@toc CONTENTS
   As mentioned in step # 10 above, typing "SYS CONFIG" will load the CNet
Pager Config file, which has numerous options. When editing values in any
of the string gadgets in the config program, remember that you can also use
these commands to help:

                   CTRL-B - go to Beginning of text.
                   CTRL-N - go to eNd of text.
                   CTRL-X - eXpell, or erase all text.
                   CTRL-K - Kill from cursor to end of line.
                BACKSPACE - Delete a character and move cursor left.
                   DELETE - Pull character to right of cursor INTO cursor.

    And now, the full descriptions for all Config options available:

                                        @{"Graphics:" link GRAPHICS}           @{"Pass to CC:" link CC}

                                 @{"Allow ChatBacks:" link CHATBACKS}            @{"Use 12 Hr:" link 12HR}
                               @{"ChatBack Access's:" link CHATBACKAC}

          @{"LogName:" link LOGNAME            @{"Ask After Log View:" link ASKLOGVIEW}

   @{"File Send Path:" link FSENDPATH}                          @{"Font:" link FONT}
  @{"Cost Percentage:" link COSTP}
   @{"File Kill Type:" link KILLT}                         @{"TEST1:" link TEST1}

   @{"Speech Options:" link SPEECHOP}
            @{"TEST2:" link TEST2}

     @{"Sound Player:" link SOUNDPL}
            @{"TEST3:" link TEST3}

            @{"SAVE" link SAVECONFIG}      @{"QUIT" link QUITCONFIG}     @{"Goto `SysOps' Screen" link SYSOPSSCREEN}      @{"TEST PAGER" link TESTPAGER}

                        @{"View Second Config Screen Options" link CONFIG2}

Pressing your ESCape key will attempt to EXIT the config file. If changes
were made, you'll first be asked if you wish to SAVE them, before you
actually leave the program.
@endnode
@node GRAPHICS "The `Graphics' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Graphics
~~~~~~~~
    "Yes"
     ~~~
        * With graphics enabled, users with 80 Columns and IBM-Ansi term
          emulation will be shown a picture similar to the Requestor that
          will be displayed on your screen.

    "No"
     ~~
        * Users with less than 80 columns, or if you choose NOT to use the
          extended graphics will be shown text: "Paging SysOp...", etc.
@endnode
@node CC "The `Pass to CC' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Pass to CC?
~~~~~~~~~~~
    "Yes"
     ~~~
        * When a user wishes to PAGE a particular SysOp, the "SysOp Port(s)"
          defined below will be checked for their ID Number. If the SysOp is
          found to be online on one of those ports, the user's "C" command
          will be converted into the appropriate "CC" command instead,
          PROVIDED that the user has ACCESS to USE the "CC" command. If they
          do NOT have access to the "CC" command, then a regular PAGE will
          be attempted.

    "No"
     ~~
        * The "CC" command will NOT be used, and a regular PAGE will be
          attempted ALL of the time.
@endnode
@node CHATBACKS "The `Allow ChatBacks' Option in Config"
Allow ChatBacks
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    "No"
     ~~
        * Set to NO and the user will ONLY be allowed to use the Pager
          ONCE per call. They'll be told they've reached the maximum number
          of times they may use the Pager if they attempt a second page.

    "Yes, ?"
     ~~~~~~
        * Where "?" is a 1, 2, or 3, which will allow the user to use the
          Pager ? additional times OVER their initial page, so a setting of
          "1" will allow the user to use the Pager TWICE(their first page,
          PLUS 1 additional page), etc. before being told they've reached
          the maximum amount.
@endnode
@node CHATBACKAC "The `ChatBack Access's' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
ChatBack Access's
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * The Access Groups that can SKIP the above ChatBack restrictictions. In
      other words, users of these access groups may use the Pager ANY NUMBER
      OF TIMES!
@endnode
@node 12HR "The `Use 12 Hr' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Use 12 Hr
~~~~~~~~~
    * Set to YES, and all references to TIMES will be made in 12 Hour format
      when using the "PagerSysAvail" editor. Set to NO, and you'll be
      shown times in 24 Hour format. (You'll also be allowed to switch
      between 12/24 hour mode from within the editor too!)
@endnode
@node LOGNAME "The `LogName' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
LogName
~~~~~~~
    * This is the FILENAME to be used to store the PAGER LOG entries when-
      ever a user pages you. The format of the log entry is as follows:

            Handle      Page Date       Reason For Paging       Paged?

    * The "Paged?" column can be one of the following three:

            "N" - You weren't available for chatting.
            "Y" - Available for chatting, and the requestor WAS displayed.
            "M" - Not available for chatting, BUT user sent MAIL instead.

    * If multiple SysOps are specified, then this name will be used as the
      STEM of the filename, where the SysOp's ID Number will complete the
      full filename. For instance, ID # 225 would have "LogName225" as the
      name of their chat log, etc.
@endnode
@node ASKLOGVIEW "The `Ask After Log View' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Ask After Log View
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    "Query w/ Yes"
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~
        * After log is displayed, you'll be ASKED if you want the log to be
          deleted. The DEFAULT answer(one used when you press RETURN) will
          be YES.

    "Query w/ No"
     ~~~~~~~~~~~
        * Same as above, but default answer will be NO.

    "Answer w/ Yes"
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
        * The log will be displayed and then AUTOMATICALLY deleted!

    "Answer w/ No"
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~
        * The log will be displayed and left INTACT on the drive!

        NOTE: Use the "SYS D" command to DELETE a log file when using
              this setting.
@endnode
@node FSENDPATH "The `File Send Path' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
File Send Path
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * This field stores the path that will be initially scanned when you
      choose the "FSend" button, although you can choose to modify this
      path from the requestor as well. Added as a hopeful means of speeding
      up finding a needed file, if you anticipate requests for files that
      are more often found in one particular path, etc. Note that the file
      requestor will ALSO be shown on the FRONT-MOST screen now!
@endnode
@node COSTP "The `Cost Percentage' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Cost Percentage
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * Allows you to specify the File Credit cost the user will be charged
      when they download the file(s) you send. Options for 1, 2, and 3
      times the file credits are included. For example, if set to "2 X",
      then the file is charged as if TWO files were downloaded, etc.

    * The ALWAYS settings affect ALL files selected by you, and will NOT
      present additional requestors, however if you choose one of those
      options NOT using the ALWAYS keyword, the selection will be used as
      the DEFAULT button of a requestor that will be presented to you as
      the Pager works through the list of files. The requestor will allow
      you to specify unique costs for each file sent to a user's Select
      List. Pressing ENTER at this requestor will activate the default
      setting you chose here.
@endnode
@node KILLT "The `File Kill Type' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
File Kill Type
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * This option allows you to specify the DEFAULT setting for what happens
      to the file(s) the user downloads. There are four settings:

        "Don't Kill Download"
         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
            * File(s) will NOT be deleted after it has been downloaded.

        "Kill After Download"
         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
            * The file(s) will be DELETED after they have been removed from
              the user's Select List(after being successfully downloaded).

        "After DL or UnSelect"
         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
            * This option means to DELETE the file, either AFTER it has
              been downloaded, OR after it has been UNSELECTED!

        "Kill After Unselected"
         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
            * The file(s) will be DELETED when the user unselects them from
              their Select Buffer, EVEN IF THEY DON'T DOWNLOAD THEM!

    * The ALWAYS settings affect ALL files selected by you, and will NOT
      present additional requestors, however if you choose one of those
      options NOT using the ALWAYS keyword, the selection will be used as
      the DEFAULT button of a requestor that will be presented to you as
      the Pager works through the list of files. The requestor will allow
      you to specify unique kill settings for each file sent to a user's
      Select List. Pressing ENTER at this requestor will activate the
      default setting you chose here.

    * Be VERY, VERY careful with this setting. If you choose one of the
      automatic settings(one NOT using the ALWAYS keyword), and a user
      requests a copy of your BBSTEXT file(or another IMPORTANT file), for
      example, then that file will be DELETED when the user finishes
      downloading it. Put mildly, this will come as an UNPLEASANT surprise
      the next time the system goes to use that file!
@endnode
@node FONT "The `Font' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Font (Size)
~~~~~~~~~~~
    * You'll be presented with a font requestor where you can choose the
      font and size you'd like to use in the display of Pager's requestor.

    * After choosing the font/size, the TEST FONT gadget will automatically
      be launched, so you can be SURE the font will look appropriate on the
      screen, or if further modification will be necessary.
@endnode
@node TEST1 "The `TEST1' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
TEST1
~~~~~
    * When you select this button(or press your "1" key), a requestor will
      pop up on your screen using the chosen font. This way, you can see how
      the chosen font looks in a requestor, before making a final decision.
@endnode
@node SPEECHOP "The `Speech Options' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Speech Options
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * This line should contain the exact settings you would use if you were
      to launch this command from a CLI shell.

    * When you get to the point where the TEXT TO BE STATED should go,
      replace it with "<TXT>" (minus the quotes). The Pager will then use
      the supplied text on the next screen in place of the "<TXT>" given
      here.

    * Two built-in defaults are also present, and can be activated by simply
      typing one word, as shown below:

            Typing "say" and pressing ENTER will use:

                    say -f -s180 -p170 <TXT>

            Typing "speak" and pressing ENTER will use:

                    echo "<TXT>" >speak:

    * You can use an alternate program in the creation of speech, but it
      will be up to YOU to figure out the correct syntax to use here.

    * If you wish NOT to use SPEECH, then empty out the string gadget(either
      by deleting with backspace or CTRL-X), then pressing your ENTER key.
      You should see the text: <USE NO SPEECH> which will tell you if you've
      successfully disabled the speech or not.
@endnode
@node TEST2 "The `TEST2' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
TEST2
~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing your "2" key) will allow you to test
      the SPEECH operations of the Pager. This way, you will know if your
      options still need a bit of tweaking before it sounds satisfactory.
@endnode
@node SOUNDPL "The `Sound Player' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Sound Player
~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * This line should contain the exact command line of the program you
      will be using to play the SOUNDS specified below.

    * If you wish NOT to use SOUND, then empty out the string gadget(either
      by deleting with backspace or CTRL-X), then pressing your ENTER key.
      You should see the text: <USE NO SOUND> which will tell you if you've
      successfully disabled the sound or not.
@endnode
@node TEST3 "The `TEST3' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
TEST3
~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing your "3" key) will allow you to test
      the SOUND operations of the Pager. You'll then be able to change the
      settings if you find a problem.
@endnode
@node SAVECONFIG "The `SAVE' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
SAVE
~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing "S") will simply SAVE the currently
      displayed settings to the config file, WITHOUT exiting the config.
@endnode
@node QUITCONFIG "The `QUIT' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
QUIT
~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing "Q") will check to see if changes
      were made(and ask if you'd like them saved), then will exit the Config
      file.
@endnode
@node SYSOPSSCREEN "The `Goto SysOps Screen' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Goto "SysOps" Screen
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing "G" or "P") will take you to the
      second screen of the Config Program that deals with the SysOps Info.
      More on this second screen described further below.

                           @{"Goto `SysOps' Screen" link CONFIG2}
@endnode
@node TESTPAGER "The `TEST PAGER' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
TEST PAGER
~~~~~~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing "T") will test your current Pager
      setup. The following will occur in this order:

        - The SOUND     will be played(if defined).
        - The SPEECH    will be orated(if defined).
        - The REQUESTOR will be displayed.

    * Note that the requestor is a "mock" requestor, and although you'll be
      able to click ANY of the buttons, NONE of them will work, but will
      simply result in ENDING the test. Again, it's used solely to make sure
      your settings look and work well for you and your system setup.
@endnode
@node CONFIG2 "On The `SysOps' Screen"
@toc CONTENTS
    The second Config Screen contains data concerning the setup of multiple
SysOps. Click the buttons to find out more information.

                                @{"Group 1:" link GROUPS}            @{"SysOp(s):" link SYSOPS}
                                Group 2:            SysOp(s):
                                Group 3:            SysOp(s):
                                Group 4:            SysOp(s):

@{"SysOp # 1:" link SYSOP1}                      @{"Sound to Play:" link SOUND2PLAY}
@{"Mail ID's:" link MAILIDS}                     @{"Port(s) Online:" link PORTSONLINE}                @{"KILL SYSOP" link KILLSYSOP}
   @{"Speech:" link SPEECH}                                                    @{"TEST SYSOP 1" link TESTSYSOP}

SysOp # 2:                      Sound to Play:
Mail ID's:                     Port(s) Online:                KILL SYSOP
   Speech:                                                    TEST SYSOP 2

                @{"Forwards Two SysOps" link FORWARDS2SYSOPS}       @{"Backwards Two SysOps" link BACK2SYSOPS}
                  @{"Previous Screen" link PREVIOUSSCREEN}           @{"ReDraw Screen" link REDRAWSCREEN}

Pressing your ESCape key will attempt to EXIT the config file. If changes
were made, you'll first be asked if you wish to SAVE them, before you
actually leave the program.
@endnode
@node GROUPS "The `Group ?:' Options in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Group ?:   SysOp(s):
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * These settings are used to create groupings of SysOps that can
      possibly be paged by your users. An example will probably be the
      easiest way to describe what these settings do. Let's take the
      following 6 SysOps:

            SysOp # 1: Joe Jones  (System SysOp)
            SysOp # 2: Joe Smith  (Message Bases)
            sysOp # 3: Joe Brown  (UD/File Bases)
            SysOp # 4: Joe Schmoe (Door Executables)
            SysOp # 5: Joe Mamma  (Paid Subscribers)
            SysOp # 6: Joe Belle  (Computer Club)

      In this example, you can see that there are a few SysOps whom you
      don't wish certain users to be able to page. For instance, users who
      are NOT subscribers shouldn't be allowed to Page SysOp # 5, non-club
      members shouldn't be allowed SysOp # 6, new users shouldn't be allowed
      2 thru 6, etc.

      This is where the GROUPINGS come in. For "Groups", you specify which
      Access Groups should be allowed to Page SysOps stated in "SysOp(s)".

      You might do something like this:

            Group 1: 0          SysOp(s): 1
            Group 2: 1-10       SysOp(s): 1-4
            Group 3: 11-20      SysOp(s): 1-5
            Group 4: 21-        SysOp(s): 1-

      These settings would then mean:

            Users of Access Group 0 could only Page SysOp # 1, while
            users of Groups 1  thru 10 could Page SysOps 1 thru 4.
            Users in Groups 11 thru 20 could Page SysOps 1 thru 5, and
            users with Groups 21 or higher could Page ANY of the SysOps.

      Make sure to NOT include the SAME access group in MORE than one group,
      as the access group found FIRST will be the one used. (For instance,
      if Group 1 above was "0,21", then access group 21 would then ONLY be
      able to Page SysOp # 1, even though in Group 4 you stated they could
      page anyone.)

      If you create a group that has access to page only ONE SysOp, then the
      menu of SysOps will NOT be shown to the user. In other words, the user
      will not even KNOW other SysOps exist!

      You don't have to use all four groupings if you don't want to. If you
      wish not to use any groupings at all, then use these values:

            Group 1: 0-         SysOp(s): 1-

      Even if you will NOT be using multiple SysOps, you should still make
      sure the above is stated.
@endnode
@node SYSOP1 "The `SysOp # ?:' Options in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
SysOp # ?:
~~~~~~~~~~
    * Enter the ID Number, Handle or Real Name for this SysOp. The info will
      be checked for validity and the user's HANDLE will be displayed in
      this area.
@endnode
@node SOUND2PLAY "The `Sound to Play' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Sound to Play
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * This should contain the path and filename of the SOUND you wish played
      whenever this SysOp is paged.

    * Clear this field out(delete, backspace, ctrl-x) if you wish to NOT
      have a sound played for this SysOp. You'll see "<USE NO SOUND>"
      displayed if the sound was turned off for this SysOp.

    * You'll see "DISABLED" displayed here if you TOTALLY disabled sound
      for ANY of the SysOps on the first screen of the config, and you will
      NOT be allowed to edit this area until you RE-ENABLE Sound on the
      first screen.
@endnode
@node MAILIDS "The `Mail ID's' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Mail ID's
~~~~~~~~~
    * If a user tries to Page a SysOp, and the "Sysop is in" menu item is
      NOT checkmarked, then the user will be asked if they wish to send
      the SysOp MAIL instead. This setting allows you to specify ALTERNATE
      mailboxes or FURTHER mailboxes if you wish the mail sent to another
      (or more than one) ID Number.

    * For example, using the SysOps from the previous example:

            SysOp # 1: Joe Jones  (System SysOp)
            SysOp # 2: Joe Smith  (Message Bases)
            SysOp # 3: Joe Brown  (UD/File Bases)
            SysOp # 4: Joe Schmoe (Door Executables)
            SysOp # 5: Joe Mamma  (Paid subscribers)
            SysOp # 6: Joe Belle  (Computer Club)

      If a user chose to Page "Joe Mamma", but he was unavailable, if the
      user then chose to leave mail instead, you might want this mail
      message to be sent to BOTH "Joe Mamma" and "Joe Jones", etc.

    * Note that these are USER ID numbers and NOT the SysOp number defined
      in the config program.
@endnode
@node PORTSONLINE "The `Port(s) Online' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Port(s) Online
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * These are the PORTS that this SysOp will MOST LIKELY be calling in on.
      The Pager looks at these ports when a user tries to Page them in case
      the probability for using the "CC" command exists.
@endnode
@node KILLSYSOP "The `KILL SYSOP' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
KILL SYSOP
~~~~~~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing "K" or "S", depending on which of
      the two SysOp entries you're dealing with), will allow you to "mark"
      this SysOp for deletion from the Pager.

    * The "SysOp # ?" value will change to "<to be deleted>" to show you
      of the upcoming action. To "undelete" the SysOp, simply go back to
      the "SysOp # ?" field and reenter that info. All other settings will
      not be affected.

    * To "officially" delete the SysOp, you will need to EXIT the config
      program. Note, however, that when a SysOp is deleted, you will LOSE
      any GROUP settings you may have previously had setup, as this data
      would no longer be valid, and would have to be recreated by you.
@endnode
@node SPEECH "The `Speech' Option in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Speech
~~~~~~
    * This is the textual string that will replace the "<TXT>" tag given in
      the "Speech options" on the first screen. Clear this value out if you
      wish to NOT have speech enabled for this SysOp. You'll see the text
      "<USE NO SPEECH>" displayed instead.

    * You'll see "DISABLED" displayed here if you TOTALLY disabled speech
      for ANY of the SysOps on the first screen of the config, and you will
      NOT be allowed to edit this area until you RE-ENABLE Speech on the
      first screen.
@endnode
@node TESTSYSOP "The `TEST SYSOP ?' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
TEST SYSOP ?
~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * The above info, as well as the current date and time and the HANDLE
      and REAL NAME of the user using the Config will be used to display
      a test Pager Screen. The following events will occur in this order:

        - The SOUND     will be played(if defined).
        - The SPEECH    will be stated(if defined).
        - The REQUESTOR will be shown.

    * Note that the requestor is a "mock" requestor, and although you'll be
      able to click ANY of the buttons, NONE of them will work, but will
      simply result in ENDING the test. Again, it's used solely to make sure
      your settings look and work well for you and your system setup.
@endnode
@node FORWARDS2SYSOPS "The `Forwards Two SysOps' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Forward Two SysOps
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing any of these: F . > + =    ) will
      display the next two SysOps.

    * Blank entries will be shown for SysOps who do not exist presently. To
      add additional SysOps, simply supply the needed "SysOp # ?" info, then
      change any of the other settings to suit.
@endnode
@node BACK2SYSOPS "The `Backwards 2 SysOps' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Backwards Two SysOps
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing any of these: B , < -    ) will
      display the previous two SysOps, if they exist.
@endnode
@node PREVIOUSSCREEN "The `Previous Screen' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
Previous Screen
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing "P" or "G") will take you back to
      the first config screen.

                            @{"Goto First Config Screen" link CONFIG}
@endnode
@node REDRAWSCREEN "The `ReDraw Screen' Button in Config"
@toc CONTENTS
ReDraw Screen
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    * Selecting this button(or pressing "R") will redraw the config screen.

    * This may come in handy in two instances:

        - You experience line noise when using the Config from Remote.
        - You enter a Handle or Real Name that was not found in your user
          data file(in which case, you'd be presented with the "Choose User"
          listing request, which will thoroughly destroy the look of your
          config screen).

    * The "R" command is also available from the first config screen, in
      case you experience line noise on that screen as well.
@endnode
@node SYSAVAIL "How to Use Pager's SysOp-Out/Availability Editor"
@toc CONTENTS
    Something NEW to v5.00 CNet Pager is the SysOp-Out/Availability Editor.
This makes creating the reasons you may not be available for chatting, as
well as setting the times you ARE available for chatting incredibly easy.

    After typing "SYS AVAIL" (or "SYS A") from a command prompt, you'll see
the main editing screen used for this editor. Here is some further info as
to how to use this editor:

    If the "Sysop is in" item, located in the "port" menu of your Control
Panel screen, is NOT checkmarked and a user attempts to page you, they'll
be told you are not around, and additionally, Pager can supply a REASON why
you aren't around. This editors main purpose is in defining those reasons.

    You'll see that all 24 hours of all seven days are visible on this one
screen. You can use the cursor arrow keys to move the > cursor to any hour
of any day.

    Pressing your ENTER key will SELECT that hour, and additionally will
advance the > cursor to the NEXT hour in the day. Pressing ENTER numerous
times will select RANGES of hours. Let's take an example to show you how
this editor is used. Let's say that normally, between the hours of midnight
and 6:00 AM you are sleeping, and that between 8:00 AM and 4:00 PM you are
working, here's what you'd do:

    - Start by positioning the > cursor on "12a" (or "000") under the "SUN"
      column.
    - Press your ENTER key seven(7) times. You'll notice that the hours
      between 12a and 6a have become highlighted in purple.
    - Now use the arrows again to position the > cursor at 12a on MON, and
      again, press ENTER seven(7) times.
    - Repeat this process for the other five days. When you've completed
      this operation, all your "sleeping" hours should now be highlighted
      in purple.
    - Now press your SPACEBAR. In the edit rectangle at the bottom of the
      editor window, you'll be able to edit the reason. (Chances are you'll
      see the current "default" reason listed). Press your BACKSPACE key to
      DELETE this reason and type "sleeping right now.". (Leave off the
      personal pronoun, as that will be supplied by Pager itself).
    - Press your ENTER key, then press "S" to tell the editor you wish to
      apply the "sleeping right now." reason to all the SELECTED hours. In
      a second or two, the editor will redraw the screen, your selected
      hours will be unselected, and you may notice the COLOR of the hours
      has changed from CYAN to YELLOW.
    - Now if you move your > cursor around the screen, you'll see that when
      you are positioned on any hour between 12a and 6a on any day, you'll
      see "He's sleeping right now." (or "She's sleeping right now.").

    - To create your WORK hours, position the > cursor next to an "8a" and
      start pressing ENTER until you've highlighted all hours between 8a
      and 4p. Do this for any additional days you work as well.
    - Press your SPACEBAR to define the reason, delete the one that's there
      and replace with text like "working to pay off the house!", etc.
    - Press ENTER, followed by "S" to copy the reason into your SELECTED
      hours again.

    - The other two options you'll see in there are CURRENT hour and DEFAULT
      hour. The CURRENT hour is the hour the > cursor is presently sitting
      next to. This is helpful if you only have ONE hour you'd like to make
      a reason for, but don't wish to SELECT the hour in the process.

    - As mentioned above, after defining reasons, the COLOR of the hours
      changes from CYAN to YELLOW. Hours left in CYAN will use a supplied
      default reason if a user should ever page you during one of these
      hours. Press SPACEBAR, create a reason and press ENTER, then press
      "D" to replace the default reason with one of your OWN reasons.

    That's all there is to creating the REASONS why you might be unavailable
to chat with a user. Use the above techniques to create as many additional
reasons as you wish. You can select hours that already have created reasons
and overwrite those hours with NEW reasons if you find the need to.

    The main POWER of the Pager is in the displaying of a custom REQUESTOR
on the SysOps frontmost screen, however in order for this requestor to show
up, you must make sure to place a checkmark next to the "Sysop is in" item
in the "port" menu of the Control Panel screen.

    Remembering to set this checkmark in place, as well as removing this
checkmark when you LEAVE the area can be a royal pain in the backside, so
starting with this version of the Pager, you can opt to use the included
AMAINT module to toggle the setting of this checkmark GLOBALLY(meaning that
it affects ALL ports). This editor is also used to specify WHEN you'd like
this checkmark to appear in the port menu. Let's take another example to see
how this is accomplished:

    From our example above, we can see that we might possibly be available
for chatting AFTER 4PM, so lets say we "want" to be available for chatting
between the hours of 5PM and 8PM Sunday through Thursday, and between 5PM
and Midnight on Friday and Saturday:

    - Move your > cursor to 5p (or "050") on SUN.
    - Press your "A" key four(4) times. You'll notice the hours between 5p
      and 8p ("050" thru "080") become highlighted in RED this time.
    - Repeat the above process for Monday through Thursday.
    - For Friday, start at 5p, but press "A" eight(8) times this time. Note
      that the hours between 5p and 12a become highlighted in RED. Also note
      how the day "wraps" over to Saturday to pick up the correct midnight.
    - Repeat this starting at 5p on Saturday.

    That's all you have to do. When you move your > cursor around the screen
this time, you'll notice a little checkmark graphic appear on the right side
of the reason box(lower right corner) whenever you're pointing at a time you
have highlighted in RED. This is helpful in reminding you that it is the RED
highlighted hours that affect the CHECKMARK status of CNet Amiga Pager.

    Once you've completed entering all your reasons, as well as defining the
hours you'll be available, press your "Q" or "ESC" keys to SAVE and EXIT the
editor.

    While IN the editor, you can also press the slash(/) key to toggle the
display between 12 hour and 24 hour format.

    This editor creates and maintains numerous text files located in your
Pager/ directory:

    Out.Sun, Out.Mon, Out.Tue, Out.Wed, Out.Thu, Out.Fri, and Out.Sat
    ~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~~      ~~~~~~~
        - These seven files hold the REASONS you're not available for each
          day of the week. Each file has 24 lines, where the first line of
          each file represents 12:00 AM ("000" hours) Midnight, while the
          last line holds data for 11:00 PM ("2300" hours).

        - If a line appears BLANK in any of these files, this means a reason
          has NOT been created for that hour, in which case the DEFAULT will
          be used instead.

    Out.Def
    ~~~~~~~
        - This file holds just one line defining the DEFAULT reason you're
          not available for chatting. It is also possible that this file
          could be BLANK as well. In this event, a hard-coded default of
          "not available for chatting right now." will be used instead.

    Availabilities
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
        - This is the file used by the AMAINT module to determine whether
          or not the "Sysop is in" item should contain a checkmark or not.
          There are seven lines in this file, which represent the seven days
          of the week(starting with SUNDAY, ending with SATURDAY). Each line
          contains a string of 24 1's and 0's, representing the 24 hours of
          the day, starting at 12:00 AM ("000" hours) MidNight on the left
          and moving rightward to 11:00 PM ("2300" hours) on the extreme
          right. A "1" means the checkmark SHOULD be used, while a "0" means
          the checkmark should be REMOVED.
@endnode
@node DOES "How Does This File Work?"
@toc CONTENTS
    Please READ the following paragraphs for more IMPORTANT information!

    There is a Priviledge Flag in each user's EA screen that is called:

            "May page the sysop"

    It's located near the bottom of the third column when you enter the
    "Priviledge flags  >>" screen.

    This priviledge flag has three settings:

         No - User is ALWAYS told you  are NOT available for chatting.

        Yes - User is ALWAYS told that you ARE available for chatting.

        Def - User is ONLY told you are available for chatting IF the
              "SysOp Is In" setting from the Control Panel's Port Menu
              has a checkmark in it. (Note that individual ports can
              use different settings, so for example, you could state
              that you are IN on ports 1-3, but OUT on ports 4-12, etc)

    This program was written to look at the setting of this priviledge flag,
and proceed accordingly.

    Use the command "SYS" to change the settings for any of the Port Menus
you wish.

    You may also wish to define a function key in your CNet CONFIG that you
can use to easily toggle your status settings for ALL Ports. Here's how
that key might look:

        "SYS * "        (minus the quotes, but remember the SPACE after
                         the * symbol).

    To use the function key to toggle your availability status manually,
simply press the key(in which case, you should see the SYS * appear on the
command line, then additionally type:

        N   and press ENTER if you are NOT available, or...
        Y   and press ENTER if you ARE available for chatting.

    So, the completed commands(before pressing ENTER) would look like the
following:

        CNet: SYS * n           <or>        CNet: SYS * y
@endnode
@node SYSCOMMAND "Using the SYS Command"
@toc CONTENTS
    From a command prompt, type "SYS ?" (minus the quotes). You'll be shown
the help screen for the SYS command. Here's what it looks like in black and
white:

CNet Amiga Pager Maint, v5.20 by Dotoran of Frontiers!

Format: <optional> [required] /=<or>

SYS                                        - List Status for ALL Ports.
SYS <[Port(s)]>                            - List Specified  Port Status.
SYS <[Port(s)]> <[S]wap/[T]oggle/[F]lip>   - Swap    Availability Status.
SYS <[Port(s)]> <[Y]es/[I]n/[A]vailable>   - Enable  Availability Status.
SYS <[Port(s)]> <[N]o/[O]ut/[U]navailable> - Disable Availability Status.

SYS <[A]vail>                              - List Pager SysAvail Editor.

SYS <[C]onfig>                             - Load Pager Config File.
SYS <[L]og/[V]iew>                         - Display Pager Log File.
SYS <[D]elete>                             - Delete  Pager Log File.
SYS <[H]elp/[?]/[/]>                       - Show This Help Menu Again.

<Key>

As you can see, there are MANY different arguments that can be used with
the new SYS command. A brief description of each form follows.

The first five forms of the command deal with the "Sysop is in" item, which
is located on the port's "Port X" menu of Control Panel:

SYS
~~~
    Typing the command with NO arguments will show you a listing of ALL your
    "SysOp Is In" statuses for all loaded ports, starting with the GLOBAL
    setting. If the global setting is enabled(Available), statuses for all
    ports will display as: [Available] (inside squared brackets), as it does
    not matter what a specific port is set to if the GLOBAL setting is set
    to ENABLED mode. You MAY see an "Unavailable" while the global setting
    states "Available". This occurs if you REMOVE a checkmark from a port
    AFTER globally placing the checkmark. Remember, though, that this kind
    of editing will NOT work correctly if you are also using the AMAINT
    module.

SYS <[Port(s)]>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    You can optionally specify one or more port numbers if you only wish to
    check the status of specific ports. Use standard CNet Ranging techniques
    if multiple ports will be selected, like this:

        SYS 0-2,12   (List status of ports 0, 1, 2, and 12 only!)

The three forms dealing with changing the states of the "Sysop is in" item
should ONLY be used if you opt NOT to use the included AMAINT file, as the
AMAINT file will affect whatever settings you choose for specific ports, and
may cause for confusion at a later date.

SYS <[Port(s)]> <[S]wap/[T]oggle/[F]lip>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    By specifying one or more ports as the first argument, followed by the
    letter S (or T or F), you can invert the availability setting for these
    ports, as shown in this example:
                                        SYS 0-2 S

            Status Before Command       Status After Command
            =====================       ====================
            Port 0: UnAvailable         Port 0: Available
            Port 1: Available           Port 1: UnAvailable
            Port 2: Available           Port 2: UnAvailable

    You can type as much of the keyword as you wish, but only the first
    letter is required to activate the command.

    You may also specify a * to signify ALL LOADED PORTS, instead of 0-.

SYS <[Port(s)]> <[Y]es/[I]n/[A]vailable>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    By specifying one or more ports as the first argument, followed by the
    letter Y (or I or A), you can ENABLE the availability setting for these
    ports, REGARDLESS of the port's present setting. This means that ports
    that do NOT have the "Sysop is in" option checkmarked WILL, and those
    that DO have it are left untouched.

    You can type as much of the keyword as you wish, but only the first
    letter is required to activate the command.

    You may also specify a * to signify ALL LOADED PORTS, instead of 0-.

SYS <[Port(s)]> <[N]o/[O]ut/[U]navailable>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    By specifying one or more ports as the first argument, followed by the
    letter N (or O or U), you can DISABLE the availability setting for these
    ports, REGARDLESS of the port's present setting. This means that ports
    that HAVE the "Sysop is in" option checkmarked will have it's checkmark
    REMOVED, while those that DO NOT have it are left untouched.

    You can type as much of the keyword as you wish, but only the first
    letter is required to activate the command.

    You may also specify a * to signify ALL LOADED PORTS, instead of 0-.

SYS <[A]vail>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Specifying an "A" for the argument will launch the Pager SysOp-Out &
    Availability Editor discussed fully earlier in this document.

SYS <[C]onfig>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    This one you already know about, but I'll mention here that you really
    only need to specify the "C" of CONFIG to enter the Pager Config file.

SYS <[L]og/[V]iew>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Typing "L" (or V) as the first parameter will show you the current PAGER
    log, provided there IS one. How you'll be asked to DELETE the log is
    configurable through the CONFIG file.

    If Multiple SysOps have been defined, and User ID # 1 uses this command,
    a listing of SysOps will be displayed. This SysOp can then view ANY of
    the defined Chat Logs.

SYS <[D]elete>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Typing "D" as the first parameter will ask if you'd like to DELETE the
    current PAGER log. This argument was added in the event you chose the
    "Answer w/ No" option for the "Ask After Log View" item in the config.

    If Multiple SysOps have been defined, and User ID # 1 uses this command,
    a listing of SysOps will be displayed. This SysOp can then delete ANY of
    the defined Chat Logs.

SYS <[H]elp/[?]/[/]>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Another one you already know about, but now you'll know you can also
    use "H" or "/" (the unshifted question mark) to get help too!

    Also, any UNKNOWN argument entered should ALSO result in the HELP
    screen being displayed to the user.
@endnode
@node SCRIPIT "What Does ScripIt / Xit Do?"
@toc CONTENTS
    This was the method I decided to go with for TERMINATING the Requestor
    without a SysOp's intervention. The "PagerKILL.sc" file in the "Pager/"
    directory is the script used to CLOSE the requestor. The ScripIt script
    language was written for ADOS 1.3, however this script works perfectly
    fine under ADOS 2.xx and 3.xx.

    The ScripIt command file is only used when I need to CLOSE the requestor.
    It is NOT being loaded and stored in memory, so should not add any more
    overhead to your system.

    I've included the "Xit" file and another script, "PagerKILL.scx" with
    the 5.00 version of Pager. The Xit program is a special version of the
    ScripIt program used to run COMPILED ScripIt scripts, which is what the
    ".scx" file is. You may wish to use THIS file instead of the ScripIt
    file for a 20K savings.

    There are two times a requestor will be closed by ScripIt:

        - If the user who created the Page logs off your bbs BEFORE the
          SysOp had a chance to click one of the buttons.

        - If the requestor was displayed on the screen for LONGER than
          5 minutes and either the same user or another user requests to
          Page the SysOp.

    There should now NEVER be a time when MORE THAN ONE requestor is ever
    displayed on your screen. If you ever see MORE THAN ONE requestor on the
    screen at once, please contact me and tell me how you did it!
@endnode
@node THANKS "Closing Info & Acknowledgments!"
@toc CONTENTS
    David Prothero originally wrote a program of this type, back in the
CNet 2.3+ days(before the new MCI system). His program acted as the frame-
work for this file. His requestor had three buttons, and did not include a
way to inform the user of the SysOp's choice, so I think OVER ALL, this
file is even BETTER than a simple CONVERSION. Thanks Dave, for giving me
the routines to look at in order to make use of the "apig.library". Even
though I am no longer using the "apig.library", I still owe Dave thanks
for giving me the gumption to figure out ANY of these external libraries!

    I'd like to also thank "Spaceman Spiff", aka Donald Knott, the SysOp who
uploaded Dave's original Pager program, asking if I could take a look at it.
He wanted to use it on his system, and as I was finishing it up, I liked it
so much, I decided to put it up on MY system. Alas, I've found that if a
program is something I like to use on MY system, there's BOUND to be someone
who'd also like it for THEIR system, so ENJOY!

    Thanks also go out to PMK (Peter M. Klein) for his insights as to how to
access the Port Menus of CNet, as well as giving me the SELFILE() routine,
which is how we can CHARGE and KILL the files we send to users using the new
FSEND button. (As a sidenote, programmers may want to rip the routines used
in this program dealing with the Select Buffer, Control Menus, and OLM's, as
all three of these areas have CHANGED their getuser values, so look at mine
to find the NEW values. At least until I finish the new getuser listing!)

    Thanks to The Brazilian (Bob Maple) for writing a file called "TISNIUM",
(The Intelligent SysOp Not In User Message), which was the file that gave me
the idea to create the separate, individual "SysOp OUT" messages. His file
was written for the CNet, v2.3? version, so I thought we should ressurrect
this feature as well.

    Thanks to Stig Joergensen of SCALA BBS for his help in figuring out how
to access the FRONT-MOST screen through intuition using ARexx. (Programmers,
that's what the "GF" routine does. It gives you the ADDRESS to use with the
"rt_screen" tag used in the "rexxreqtools.library"...)

    And lastly, for v4.0, Thanks to Aunt Bea (Henry Priebe) for telling me
about the "ScripIt" language, which is how we can finally get rid of the
Pager Requestor if the user should log off(or after 5 minutes). He also let
me know the correct usage of the SPEAK handler, after numerous failed
attempts on my part using COPY and LIST, instead of ECHO. Dih!

    Enjoy this file, and if you find any bugs, or wish it had something it
presently does NOT have, then feel free to drop me some feedback!

                                                                 - Dotoran!
In the Future:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    I'd also like to make the ability, so that if you select the "CHAT"
button from the requestor, it will open that user's screen(if not already
open), bring that screen to the front, and then immediately enter CHAT
mode for you! I'd still like to do this, however we've discovered a bug
in the OPENDISPLAY ARexx command in CNet, so until this command is fixed,
this addition will be put on hold. This bug still exists in CNet, v4.25a,
so until Ray can track this one down, again we wait... :-(
                                                                 - Dotoran!
@endnode
@node UPGRADE "What to do with earlier Pager versions!"
@toc CONTENTS
    v5.20 Pager had modifications made to it which SHOULD allow it to be 
used by BOTH CNet, v3.05c AND v4.26e+ SysOps, with no further modification
on YOUR parts.

    If you're coming from a version of Pager 4.00 or EARLIER, then you'll
need to completely PURGE your old version and install this NEW version for
the first time.

    If you're using v5.00 of Pager, then you'll need to run the included
"PagerUpdate" file to make the needed changes to your config files. If you
upgraded to v5.13 already, then you do NOT need to run the update program.

  @{"Install For The First Time" link INSTALL}   @{"Using Pager Config" link CONFIG}   @{"Using SysAvail Editor" link SYSAVAIL}
@endnode
